From: Kari.Hurtta@Helsinki.FI (Kari E. Hurtta)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.linux.help
Subject: Re: USERS CAN DELETE ROOT  FILES!!
Date: 20 Nov 1993 21:25:10 GMT

You have misunderstand semantic of protection fields.

Of course users can delete root's files if files are in directory which users
have write access. Creating or deleting file requires ability to modify
directory (ie. write access to directory). Deleting don't touch file's content 
(except that one directory entry for that file is removed and if it was last
 directory entry (ie. link) to that file, file space is freed.) So write access
to file isn't required (other words: to deleting file you need not write to 
file.)

--
- K E H                                      /  Elämä on monimutkaista
  Kari.Hurtta@Helsinki.FI

