From: hedrick@geneva.rutgers.edu (Charles Hedrick)
Subject: Re: how fast is linux?
Date: 20 Nov 93 23:01:25 GMT

grante@hydro.rosemount.com (Grant Edwards) writes:

>: I am thinking about upgrading to linux but a friend told me it ran
>: slow.

>He's right, man!  I run Linux and X11 on a 368DX-25, 8MB, no cache and
>a herc monochrome board.  X performance and usability suck rocks
>compared to a SPARC-10 with 32MB, a 19 inch color monitor.

I assume the reply is a joke, the point being that speed of an OS
depends upon the hardware configuration.  My own experience and that
of others on the net is that Linux manages to get reasonable
performance out of minimal hardware, and performs very well indeed
with good hardware.  Performance seems to be better for given hardware
than most other Unix or Unix-like systems.  There are two cases where
one might complain about performance (1) if your hardware isn't right
for what you're doing.  E.g. you probably want 8MB if you're going to
run X.  There are certainly machines on which you could get reasonable
Microsoft Windows performance (assuming you weren't running anything
big under MS Windows), but X under Linux would be terrible.  However
if X under Linux is terrible on a given piece of hardware, X wouldn't
be any better (and would probably be much worse) under other Unix
clones.  (2) if you have problems with BIOS settings.  A few people
have reported bad Linux performance, and it's turned out to be bad
settings of obscure parameters in the BIOS.  Again, I believe other
Unix implementations and Unix clones are likely to use the processor
similarly to Linux.

Under most situations, Linux performs very well indeed.

